Any idea how to fix that? This makes it hard to use pull-request triggers with code guru

I was testing out this tool in my local repository with a full scan before fully integrating it into the CICD pipeline. For some reason it was taking already over 1.5 hours to do a single scan (without completing), yet it only took less than 10 minutes when scanning the sample repo.

I recloned my local repo into a different folder (without having any packages installed or downloaded) and tried again. Took less than 10 minutes and completed successfully. huh.

I am now very worried what my up and coming cloud bill will look like.

**Please fix the tool so that it does not scan untracked (gitignore'd) files in the database, or at least warn of this behavior**

(Untracked files generally shouldn't exist if this is only used in a pipeline, but most certainly will affect those testing out the tool on their repo for the first time)

I was testing out this tool in my local repository with a full scan before fully integrating it into the CICD pipeline. For some reason it was taking already over 1.5 hours to do a single scan (without completing), yet it only took less than 10 minutes when scanning the sample repo.

I recloned my local repo into a different folder (without having any packages installed or downloaded) and tried again. Took less than 10 minutes and completed successfully. huh.

I am now very worried what my up and coming cloud bill will look like.

**Please fix the tool so that it does not scan untracked (gitignore'd) files in the database, or at least warn of this behavior**

(Untracked files generally shouldn't exist if this is only used in a pipeline, but most certainly will affect those testing out the tool on their repo for the first time)

If you scan without a commit range, it uploads the entire folder and analyzes everything in there. So, this allows you to also scan folders that are not under version control.

What would be your preferred behavior? Should it respect the gitignore file automatically? Should it ask if it detects a gitignore file?

'I have a pull request from a fork:

both the fork and the original repo are allow-listed in my role:
```
    - name: Assume IAM Role
      continue-on-error: true
      uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v1
      id: iam-role
      with:
        role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::048169001733:role/GuruGitHubCICDRole
        aws-region: us-west-2

```
when I trigger only on pull_request, the action fails to get credentials:
https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-codeguru-samples/runs/5030685457?check_suite_focus=true

However, when I trigger on push it works:
https://github.com/martinschaef/amazon-codeguru-samples/runs/5030736213?check_suite_focus=true

Any idea how to fix that? This makes it hard to use pull-request triggers with code guru

'author_association': 'NONE', 'body': "Oh ... so it looks like you need the `id-token: write` permission to set this variable and the maximum level for that permission across forks is `read` according to the GitHub documentation:
https://docs.github.com/en/actions/security-guides/automatic-token-authentication#permissions-for-the-github_token
So you basically can't use this way of authenticating for Pull Requests.

https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-codeguru-samples/pull/10
both the fork and the original repo are allow-listed in my role:
```
    - name: Assume IAM Role
      continue-on-error: true
      uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v1
      id: iam-role
      with:
        role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::048169001733:role/GuruGitHubCICDRole
        aws-region: us-west-2

```
when I trigger only on pull_request, the action fails to get credentials:
https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-codeguru-samples/runs/5030685457?check_suite_focus=true

However, when I trigger on push it works:
https://github.com/martinschaef/amazon-codeguru-samples/runs/5030736213?check_suite_focus=true

Any idea how to fix that? This makes it hard to use pull-request triggers with code guru
